<doc id="450004" wikidata="Q1473526" url="?curid=450004" title="Jacobi elliptic functions">
<text>In mathematics, the Jacobi elliptic functions are a set of basic elliptic functions. They are found in the description of the motion of a pendulum, as well as in the design of electronic elliptic filters. While trigonometric functions are defined with reference to a circle, the Jacobi elliptic functions are a generalization which refer to other conic sections, the ellipse in particular. The relation to trigonometric functions is contained in the notation, for example, by the matching notation formula_1 for formula_2. The Jacobi elliptic functions are used more often in practical problems than the Weierstrass elliptic functions as they do not require notions of complex analysis to be defined and/or understood. They were introduced by . Carl Friedrich Gauss had already studied special Jacobi elliptic functions in 1797, the lemniscate elliptic functions in particular, but his work was published much later.

==Overview==
There are twelve Jacobi elliptic functions denoted by formula_3, where formula_4 and formula_5 are any of the letters formula_6, formula_7, formula_8, and formula_9. (Functions of the form formula_10 are trivially set to unity for notational completeness.) formula_11 is the argument, and formula_12 is the parameter, both of which may be complex. In fact, the Jacobi elliptic functions are meromorphic in both formula_11 and formula_12. The distribution of the zeros and poles in the formula_11-plane is well-known. However, questions of the distribution of the zeros and poles in the formula_12-plane remain to be investigated.

In the complex plane of the argument formula_11, the twelve functions form a repeating lattice of simple poles and zeroes. Depending on the function, one repeating parallelogram, or unit cell, will have sides of length formula_18 or formula_19 on the real axis, and formula_20 or formula_21 on the imaginary axis, where formula_22 and formula_23 are known as the quarter periods with formula_24 being the elliptic integral of the first kind. The nature of the unit cell can be determined by inspecting the &quot;auxiliary rectangle&quot; (generally a parallelogram), which is a rectangle formed by the origin formula_25 at one corner, and formula_26 as the diagonally opposite corner. As in the diagram, the four corners of the auxiliary rectangle are named formula_7, formula_6, formula_9, and formula_8, going counter-clockwise from the origin. The function formula_31 will have a zero at the formula_4 corner and a pole at the formula_5 corner. The twelve functions correspond to the twelve ways of arranging these poles and zeroes in the corners of the rectangle.

When the argument formula_11 and parameter formula_12 are real, with formula_36, formula_37 and formula_38 will be real and the auxiliary parallelogram will in fact be a rectangle, and the Jacobi elliptic functions will all be real valued on the real line.

Since the Jacobian elliptic functions are doubly periodic in formula_11, they factor through a torus – in effect, their domain can be taken to be a torus, just as cosine and sine are in effect defined on a circle. Instead of having only one circle, we now have the product of two circles, one real and the other imaginary. The complex plane can be replaced by a complex torus. The circumference of the first circle is formula_19 and the second formula_21, where formula_37 and formula_38 are the quarter periods. Each function has two zeroes and two poles at opposite positions on the torus. Among the points there is one zero and one pole.

The Jacobian elliptic functions are then doubly periodic, meromorphic functions satisfying the following properties:
* There is a simple zero at the corner formula_4, and a simple pole at the corner formula_5.
* The complex number formula_46 is equal to half the period of the function formula_47; that is, the function formula_47 is periodic in the direction formula_49, with the period being formula_50. The function formula_47 is also periodic in the other two directions formula_52 and formula_53, with periods such that formula_54 and formula_55 are quarter periods.


==Notation==

The elliptic functions can be given in a variety of notations, which can make the subject unnecessarily confusing. Elliptic functions are functions of two variables. The first variable might be given in terms of the amplitude formula_56, or more commonly, in terms of formula_11 given below. The second variable might be given in terms of the parameter formula_12, or as the elliptic modulus formula_59, where formula_60, or in terms of the modular angle formula_61, where formula_62. The complements of formula_59 and formula_12 are defined as formula_65 and formula_66. These four terms are used below without comment to simplify various expressions.

The twelve Jacobi elliptic functions are generally written as formula_3 where formula_4 and formula_5 are any of the letters formula_6, formula_7, formula_8, and formula_9. Functions of the form formula_10 are trivially set to unity for notational completeness. The “major” functions are generally taken to be formula_75, formula_76 and formula_77 from which all other functions can be derived and expressions are often written solely in terms of these three functions, however, various symmetries and generalizations are often most conveniently expressed using the full set. (This notation is due to Gudermann and Glaisher and is not Jacobi&#x27;s original notation.)

Throughout this article, formula_78.

